data.content:
Here's the summary of the two APIs:

### 1. Strongly-typed metadata
```csharp
JsonTypeInfo<WeatherForecast> typedInfo =
    (JsonTypeInfo<WeatherForecast>)options.GetTypeInfo(typeof(WeatherForecast));
```
`GetTypeInfo(Type)` returns the non-generic `JsonTypeInfo`; cast it to `JsonTypeInfo<T>` to get the typed version. You can then pass it straight to `JsonSerializer.Serialize(value, typedInfo)`.

### 2. Probe without throwing
```csharp
if (options.TryGetTypeInfo(typeof(T), out JsonTypeInfo? info))
{
    // metadata is available – use it
}
```
`TryGetTypeInfo` (added in .NET 9) returns `false` instead of throwing when the resolver doesn't support the requested type — ideal for branching on "have it" vs. "don't have it" without `try/catch`.

The demo showed both: the reflection resolver happily returns metadata for any type, while a source-gen resolver (`SmallContext`) that only knows about `int` returns `false` for `WeatherForecast` and `string`.
